 form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Yaqub  ,   Yakub  ,   Yacoub  , or   Yacob  , Slovenian   Jakob   and <b>Jakop</b>, Czech and Slovak   Jakub  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Jacobs   and   Jacobson  ). The name <i>Jacob</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Chacko  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]}]},{"name":"Volta","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (northern):","habitational name from any of numerous places called with the word <i>volta</i> ‘turn’, ‘vault’.","from a shortened form of a medieval personal name such as <i>Bonavolta</i>, literally ‘good fortune’, or <i>Malavolta</i> ‘bad fortune’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ingone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Ingoe in Stamfordham (Northumb)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ingo","meanings":["From the medieval Spanish given name <i>Íñigo</i>, a vernacular derivative of   Ignatius  , apparently the result of crossing with a name recorded in the Middle Ages as <i>Ennecus</i>. This is of uncertain, possibly Basque, origin. <i>Íñigo</i> is now rarely used as a given name in Spain. In the English-speaking world it is mainly associated with the architect and stage designer  Inigo Jones  (  1573–1652 ). The name had previously been borne by his father, a London clothmaker, who may well have received it at around the time of  Queen Mary's  marriage to  Philip of Spain , when Spanish ways and Spanish names were fashionable, especially among devout Roman Catholics. The architect passed it on to his son, but later examples are infrequent."]}]